	]a
	" submitted 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=two|href=/3811S)
	" 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=submissions|href=/3810S)
	" for games based on the My Little Pony franchise. Both were rejected not for optimization issues but for not being "serious games" as this was during the time the Vault class existed. So what does that even mean? Good question, since going by the 
	[a href=https://tasvideos.org/LegacyPages/Vault?revision=28 rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"now archived legacy Vault page from around when both were judged
	]a
	" it was completely nebulous for games that weren't board games, game shows, and/or sports games. Even the judge who rejected it noted that "serious game" clause was subjective, as noted in their 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=post in the DS game's submission post rejection|href=/Forum/Posts/338743)
	". In other words, the old submission was a victim of the more restrictive and ultimately more arbitrary game choice rules of the 2010s. Thankfully TASVideos is more open to what's acceptable which is actually a lot cooler.
	$LF
